{"id":"d222c2723514","content":"The full story of modernizing a decade-old SaaS asset pipeline — without breaking production\n\n9 min read\n1 hour ago\n\n--\n\nPress enter or click to view image in full size\n\nI work in a SaaS company with a strong foothold in the aviation industry. When Rails 7 officially deprecated Webpacker and Rails 8 doubled down on Propshaft as the default asset pipeline, the writing was on the wall. For our platform — a large, multi-tenant SaaS application with over a decade of history — “we’ll get to it eventually” finally became “it’s now or never.”\nThis is the story of a eight-month migration that touched 318 files, spanning 4,303 additions and 7,899 deletions across 234 commits. It was messy, instructive, and ultimately worth it. Here’s everything I learned.\n\nWhat We Were Working With\nThis wasn’t a typical rails new app. Built over ten years, it had accumulated a considerable frontend footprint:\n\n• Webpacker 5 (Webpack 4 under the hood) managing React components, TypeScript, and Stimulus controllers\n\n• Sprockets serving jQuery plugins, Bootstrap stylesheets, legacy vendor scripts, and Rails engine assets\n\n• Two asset pipelines running simultaneously — the classic “dual pipeline” antipattern\n\n• Multiple JavaScript entrypoints: the main application, login, kiosk, admin panels, and a full React + GraphQL interactive UI\n\n• A mountable Rails engine with its own JavaScript and SCSS assets\n\n• jQuery, jQuery UI, jQuery Migrate, lodash, Chart.js, Select2, jCrop, Minicolors — the full legacy buffet\n\n• HAML views with inline JavaScript referencing globally-scoped functions\nIn short, this was an asset pipeline migration on hard mode.\n\nChoosing the Target Architecture\nBefore writing a single line of code, I evaluated the options Rails offers:\nPress enter or click to view image in full size\n\nThe decision: jsbundling-rails with Webpack 5 + Propshaft.\nWhy not esbuild? With 200+ JavaScript/TypeScript files, complex Webpack aliases, vendor shims, and a React + GraphQL setup, esbuild’s lack of full Webpack-compatible plugin support would have added migration risk. Keeping Webpack — but removing the Webpacker gem’s opinionated wrapper — gave us the control we needed without rewriting every build configuration from scratch.\nWhy Propshaft over keeping Sprockets? Sprockets was the root cause of half our asset headaches: image-url() vs url(), asset precompilation surprises, engine asset registration failures. Propshaft's simplicity was exactly what we needed.\n\nThe Migration Plan: Six Phases\nPhase 1: Audit Everything (Week 1)\nThe single most valuable thing I did. Before touching code, I documented:\n\n• Every React component and its entry point\n\n• Every JavaScript dependency and how it was loaded (Webpacker pack, Sprockets require, CDN, or inline script tag)\n\n• Every image-url(), asset-url(), and asset_path call in SCSS and views\n\n• Every layout file and which packs/assets it referenced\n\n• Every inline <script> that relied on globally-scoped functions\nThis audit revealed more than 10 globally-scoped functions that inline view scripts depended on — something that would break silently once we moved to ES modules.\nPhase 2: Set Up the New Pipeline (Week 2)\nAdded jsbundling-rails and propshaft to the Gemfile. Removed legacy asset-wrapper gems in a single commit:\n# Removed -- example gems that is Ruby wrappers around npm packages\ngem 'bootstrap'\ngem 'jcrop-rails-v2'\ngem 'jquery-migrate-rails'\ngem 'jquery-rails'\ngem 'jquery-ui-rails'\ngem 'lodash-rails'\ngem 'popper_js'\ngem 'sprockets-rails'# Added\ngem 'jsbundling-rails'\ngem 'propshaft'Every one of those removed gems was replaced by its npm equivalent, giving us direct control over JavaScript dependency versions.\nPhase 3: The PDF Gem Surprise\nIf your application generates PDFs (e.g., with wicked_pdf or grover), beware: many PDF gems hardcode Sprockets asset helpers. When you switch to Propshaft, PDF generation breaks because the gem can't resolve your stylesheets through the new pipeline.\nSolution: We forked the PDF gem and patched the asset resolution to work with Propshaft’s simpler path-based approach. This was a full afternoon of debugging for what turned out to be a ~20-line patch.\nLesson: Before migrating, audit every gem that touches assets. Any gem that uses ActionView::Helpers::AssetUrlHelper or Sprockets-specific APIs is a potential landmine. Common offenders:\n\n• wicked_pdf / grover / puppeteer-ruby (PDF generation)\n\n• graphiql-rails (stopped auto-registering Sprockets assets after v1.10)\n\n• administrate or other admin panel gems\n\n• Any gem that ships its own app/assets directory\nPhase 4: The Webpack Config (Weeks 2–3)\nWith Webpacker gone, we needed a standalone webpack.config.js. This was the most technically involved phase. Key architectural decisions:\n// 1. Multiple entrypoints matching the layout structure\nentry: {\n'application-bundle': './client/bundles/application-bundle.ts',\n'login-bundle': './client/bundles/login-bundle.ts',\n'kiosk-bundle': './client/bundles/kiosk-bundle.ts',\n// ... 8+ entrypoints\n},// 2. Output to app/assets/builds so Propshaft picks them up\noutput: {\npath: path.resolve(__dirname, 'app/assets/builds'),\nfilename: '[name].js',\n},\n// 3. Aliases to replace Sprockets' asset path magic\nresolve: {\nalias: {\n'@vendor': path.resolve(__dirname, 'vendor/assets/javascripts'),\n'jquery': require.resolve('jquery'),\n},\n},The package.json scripts also changed:\n{\n\"scripts\": {\n\"build\": \"webpack --config webpack.config.js\",\n\"build:watch\": \"webpack serve --config webpack.config.js --progress\",\n\"build:analyze\": \"webpack --config webpack.config.js --mode production --analyze\"\n}\n}No more bin/webpack or bin/webpack-dev-server -- those were Webpacker shims we no longer need.\nPhase 5: The Great Import Migration (Weeks 3–5)\nThis was the most tedious phase. Every file that used Sprockets directives needed conversion:\nBefore (Sprockets):\n//= require jquery\n//= require jquery_ujs\n//= require lodash\n//= require_tree .After (ES modules):\nimport $ from 'jquery'\nimport 'jquery-ujs'\nimport _ from 'lodash'\n// Explicit imports for each file -- no more require_treeFor SCSS, every image-url() became url(), and every @import pointing to a gem-provided path became an npm or @vendor aliased import:\nBefore:\nbackground-image: image-url('icons/print.png');\n@import \"bootstrap/variables\";After:\nbackground-image: url('/assets/icons/print.png');\n@import \"@vendor/bootstrap/variables\";Phase 6: The Global Scope Problem (Weeks 4–5)\nThis was the pitfall that cost the most debugging time.\nSprockets and Webpacker 5 would sometimes leak module contents into the global scope. Dozens of our HAML/ERB views relied on this:\n:javascript\n$(document).ready(function() {\nlabelFormatter('#my-chart', data);\n});After migrating to proper ES modules, labelFormatter is no longer global -- it's scoped to its module. Every such function silently becomes undefined at runtime, with no build-time error to warn you.\nThe fix required a globals.js file with explicit window attachments:\nimport { labelFormatter } from './charts'window.labelFormatter = labelFormatterWe also built a small helper to expose asset URLs via window.ASSETS, replacing the old asset_path calls that React components used to reference images:\n# Helper: exposes asset paths to JavaScript\nmodule AssetsIncludeHelper\ndef asset_script_tag\n# Makes asset URLs available via window.ASSETS\n# React components access them through an assetsRef() utility\nassets = case name\nwhen :react_images\n{\nlogo: asset_path('logo.png'),\n}\nelse\n{}\nend javascript_tag do\n\"window.ASSETS = Object.assign(window.ASSETS || {}, #{assets.to_json});\".html_safe\nend\nend\nend\nBefore (React component):\n<img src={require('../../assets/logo.png')} />After:\n<img src={assetsRef('logo.png')} />\nThe Pitfalls Nobody Warns You About\n1. jQuery Module Resolution Is a Nightmare\njQuery plugins expect $ to be global. Some npm-packaged jQuery plugins import their own copy of jQuery, creating duplicates. Others expect window.jQuery to exist. With Webpack 5 and ES modules, you must explicitly configure jQuery resolution:\n// webpack.config.js\nresolve: {\nalias: {\n'jquery': require.resolve('jquery'),\n},\n},\nplugins: [\nnew webpack.ProvidePlugin({\n$: 'jquery',\njQuery: 'jquery',\n}),\n],Even with this, some plugins (Select2, Minicolors, jQuery UI) needed manual import ordering and explicit window.$ assignments. This single issue consumed an entire week of debugging across the codebase.\n2. Rails Engine Assets Need Special Attention\nIf your app has mountable Rails engines with their own JavaScript and SCSS, beware. With Sprockets, engine assets “just worked” because Sprockets walked every engine’s app/assets directory automatically. With Propshaft + Webpack, you need to explicitly:\n\n• Add engine JavaScript paths to Webpack’s resolve.modules or create aliases\n\n• Create separate entry points for engine-specific bundles\n\n• Conditionally load engine bundles in layouts\n-# Only load the engine's JS bundle when inside that engine's namespace\n- if controller.class.module_parent == MyEngine\n= javascript_include_tag 'my_engine_bundle'3. Bootstrap Gem to npm Bootstrap Transition\nIf you serve Bootstrap via a Ruby gem (which wraps the Sprockets-based distribution), removing the gem while keeping things working requires careful alias management. The gem’s SCSS import paths differ from npm’s, so every @import \"bootstrap/...\" needs path adjustments.\nIf you’re in the unfortunate position of running both Bootstrap 3 and Bootstrap 5 (as we were during a gradual migration), this gets even more complex — each version needs its own import alias.\n4. CSS image-url() to url() -- More Than Find-and-Replace\nSprockets’ image-url() helper resolves asset-fingerprinted paths at compile time. A simple find-and-replace to url() works for Propshaft, but only if the path is correct relative to Propshaft's asset load paths. Print icons, PDF backgrounds, email template images -- each path needed manual verification.\n5. System Tests Break in Subtle Ways\nAfter the migration, system specs started failing with timing issues. Assets now loaded differently (Webpack dev server vs Sprockets on-the-fly compilation), and tests needed “wait for ajax” in places that previously \"just worked\" because Sprockets compilation was synchronous. This was a recurring theme across spec files in our test suite.\n6. CI Pipeline Changes\nCI (CircleCI) needed several updates:\n\n• Remove the Webpacker-specific bin/webpack precompile step\n\n• Add yarn build before rails assets:precompile\n\n• Update the Chrome version for compatibility with new asset loading patterns\n\nWhat Went Right\n1. Incremental Migration Over a Feature Branch\nWe used a single long-lived feature branch with regular merges from the main branch. This resulted in few merge commits resolving conflicts across Gemfile.lock, yarn.lock, and shared entrypoints. It was painful but better than a big-bang deploy that could break production.\n2. The Audit-First Approach\nDocumenting every asset dependency before coding saved us from dozens of “why did this break?” debugging sessions. If you take away one thing from this article: audit first, migrate second.\n3. Keeping Webpack\nBy choosing jsbundling-rails with Webpack rather than switching to esbuild, we avoided rewriting our entire build configuration. The Webpack config is now a standalone webpack.config.js that we fully own -- no gem abstraction layer in between. Upgrades and customizations are straightforward.\n4. Removing of Ruby Gems\nEvery gem that was just a Ruby wrapper around an npm package is now gone. This means:\n\n• Faster bundle install\n\n• No more version mismatches between the gem’s bundled JS and what npm provides\n\n• Direct control over JavaScript dependency versions via package.json\n\n• One fewer place to look when debugging asset issues\n\nBy the Numbers\nPress enter or click to view image in full size\n\nGuidance for Teams Considering This Migration\nDo This If…\n\n• You’re planning a Rails 8 upgrade (Webpacker does not work with Rails 8)\n\n• You’re suffering from the dual-p"}